{
  "title": "Combining HMAC and Typing for Production Code in Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This guide demonstrates the usage of HMAC (Hash-based Message Authentication Code) and Type Hints in Python 3.12+ for secure message authentication and type safety in production code.",
  "key_points": [
    "HMAC provides a way to ensure data integrity and authenticity",
    "Type hints improve the readability, maintainability, and robustness of the code",
    "Python 3.12+ introduces several improvements related to HMAC and type hinting",
    "Combining both techniques enhances security and reliability in production environments"
  ],
  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "```\nimport hmac\nfrom typing import Final, Any\n\n# Define your secret key as a final variable\nSECRET_KEY: Final[bytes] = b'my-secret-key'\n\ndef hmac_sha256(message: bytes, key: bytes) -> bytes:\n    return hmac.new(key, message, hashlib.sha256).digest()\n\ndef authenticate_message(message: bytes) -> bool:\n    correct_hash = hmac_sha256(message, SECRET_KEY)\n    returned_hash = hmac_sha256(message, SECRET_KEY)\n    return correct_hash == returned_hash\n```"
    }
  ],
  "version_notes": [
    "Python 3.12+ includes improvements in the HMAC module and type hinting support",
    "This example uses Final type hints for defining immutable variables, and Annotated[Any] for flexibility when using built-in functions without explicit type hints"
  ],
  "caveats": [
    "Always choose a strong secret key to ensure secure message authentication",
    "Remember to replace 'my-secret-key' with your own secure key in production environments"
  ]
}
